<http://example.com/water-regulation/permit/043462/outlet/1/effluent/1#geography> a geo:Geometry ;
    ns1:crs <http://www.opengis.net/def/crs/EPSG/0/27700> ;
    ns1:gridReferenceLevel <http://example.com/water-regulation/grid-level/site> ;
    geo:asWKT "<http://www.opengis.net/def/crs/EPSG/0/27700> POINT(384760 94630)"^^geo:wktLiteral ;
    rdfs:comment "The discharge SITE's National Grid Reference from the consents register (EPSG:27700), verbatim. It is a site-level, 100 m reference inherited by every outlet of every permit at that site - see ttl/regulation/README.md and app/points.html. Coarse, and reproduced as published." .

<http://example.com/water-regulation/permit/043462/outlet/1/effluent/1#geography-effluent> a geo:Geometry ;
    ns1:crs <http://www.opengis.net/def/crs/EPSG/0/27700> ;
    ns1:gridReferenceLevel <http://example.com/water-regulation/grid-level/effluent> ;
    geo:asWKT "<http://www.opengis.net/def/crs/EPSG/0/27700> POINT(385080 94000)"^^geo:wktLiteral ;
    rdfs:comment "The register's grid reference for this outlet/effluent specifically, as opposed to the SITE reference the store publishes as the discharge point's default geometry. Published so that app/points.html can score a proximity join against ALL THREE references the register carries, rather than only the coarsest one - the strongest version of the counter-argument, computed rather than asserted." .

<http://example.com/water-regulation/permit/043462/outlet/1/effluent/1#geography-outlet> a geo:Geometry ;
